title: For Sale:  EoTech 552 with Night Vision
postcontent:
This EoTech is the model that includes the night vision mode and uses AA batteries with the controls in the rear of the unit. This is also the same model that is standard for military units such as the 10th Mountain and Stryker divisions not to mention it is the selected model by ATF, FBI, and the DEA.

Due to the EoTech having the dot within a 65 MOA circle reticle nothing is faster on targets up close.  I have found that I am able to quickly and easily hit a 10" plate offhand at 300 yards with the central 1 MOA dot (match ammo in a 1/2 minute capable rifle holding 4-5 inches over with a 50 yard zero). This model, though not a true QD, will mount in seconds without tools and if placed on the same slot as the one used to zero will return to zero (I have never been able to detect a zero shift at the distances it's intended for which is 0-200 yards).

This unit has been on my training rifle for several years and it has the nicks and scrapes to prove it. Even though it shows that it has been used it functions in every way as it should. That is why people who put their lives on the line use these. 

This model EoTech sells for $569 new. $300 is my price and I believe that it is very reasonable.  If you are thinking about a lowball offer don't wast your time, I will not respond.  I am generally not interested in a trade but I have been offered items in the past that have changed my mind. Typically I respond quickly to email but at times due to my erratic schedule it may be the following day.

title: For Sale:  Henry 45/70 Blued Walnut
postcontent:
A caliber that traces its origins from the battlefield to its modern-day presence in hunting camps across the country.

Our lever gun offerings have progressed from .17 and .22 caliber rimfires, to pistol cartridge centerfires and in 2011 to the most popular deer-hunting caliber of all - the .30-30. Now for 2012 we are introducing a new model chambered for a famous cartridge capable of handling even the largest game in North America. That's right: We now make .45-70 lever actions!

Introduced by the U.S. Army in 1873, this cartridge was first known as the .45 Government. As it made its way into commercially produced firearms the name .45-70 appeared, because it was loaded with a 70 grain blackpowder charge with 405 and 500 grain bullets. Virtually all rifle making companies of the late 19th century chambered their single shots and lever actions for the .45-70. As those companies and their rifles faded away, the .45-70's popularity did not. Factory .45-70 ammunition has been cataloged continuously since 1873 but never in the variety of loadings available now, in the 21st century. They range from 405 grain lead bullet, low-velocity loads for deer hunting and target shooting to high-velocity 300 to 400 grain jacketed bullet ones meant for large game.

Our new Model H010 .45-70 can handle them all. Its receiver is blued steel fitted with an 18.43" round barrel underneath and a tubular magazine of four-round capacity. Its pistol-grip buttstock and steel-capped forend are crafted of beautiful American walnut and cut with checkering to provide a sure grip. The buttstock wears a soft rubber pad to help shooters handle .45-70 recoil from a 7.08 lb. rifle. The model H010 will be factory issued with XS Ghost Ring rear peep sight with blade front. Because the receiver is drilled and tapped, scope mounting is an easy option.

If you need a handy yet powerful lever gun capable of fast repeat shots in the bear country of Alaska, or just a short, light rifle for deer hunting in the mountains of Pennsylvania, our new Model H010 will provide the accuracy and reliability you can count on.

title: For Sale:  Arsenal SGL 21 (Russian-built 7.62x39 AK rifle)
location: I'm located in Owatonna, MN, Rochester, MN, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale is my Arsenal SGL 21. This rifle was built in Izhevsk, Russia (and this is stamped on the receiver) at the Izhmash Factory in Izhevsk (SAIGA brand) - the same factory that builds AK-47s and 74s for the Russian Government - and was imported by Arsenal, Inc. of Las Vegas. I purchased this rifle new in July of 2012 and have fired 360 rounds through it. Like all of my firearms, I have cleaned the rifle meticulously after each range outing. The finish on the rifle remains in perfect condition except for slight wear at the magazine well. The rifle has a cold-hammer-forged (CHF) barrel with a chromed bore and chamber. The rifle does have the side accessory rail for mounting optics. The rifle has the traditional Warsaw-length stock. The rifle has the traditional two-stage trigger which I have always found to have a very clean break and positive reset. I have made no modifications whatsoever to the rifle and like all Arsenal rifles it has matching serial numbers for all numbered components. I have never experienced a single malfunction with the rifle and there is nothing wrong with it; I am selling the rifle to help fund an IWI Tavor.

Included with the rifle is:
-OD Russian Military Sling (sold by Arsenal)
-Arsenal front-sight adjustment tool
-60 rounds of 7.62x39 (WPA brand)
-6 magazines (1 Arsenal 10 round magazine; 1 polymer Tapco magazine; 4 polish steel magazines (two of which are unused and still in original packaging) - all magazines were purchased brand new)

Please contact me with any questions or additional picture requests.

Thanks and good luck!
